snapshot date of 5th April 2017.   Mean Hourly Pay Gap: 28.08%  Median Hourly Pay Gap: 27.65%  Mean Bonus Pay Gap: 37.31%  Median Bonus Pay Gap: 50.95%   Traditionally more men than women pursued careers in the IT sector and this trend continues today.  There is a national and well documented shortage of qualified and experienced females for technology roles, such as Software Engineering, Software Architecture and Cyber Security and this is reflected at MHR with a higher proportion of men in senior technical and senior management roles. The pay gap is caused by the fact that women hold fewer senior roles, as can be seen by the figures in the upper middle and upper quartiles.  The bonus pay data tells a similar story, as bonuses are awarded to the senior positions, which are mainly occupied by men.  However, where employees are entitled to a bonus there is just under a 2% difference between the percentage of men and women who received bonus payments.  Proportion of employees awarded a bonus in the 12 months prior the snapshot date:   Men - 21.78%  Women - 19.82%   MHR are committed to fairness and equality and are working to reduce the gender pay gap by ensuring equal participation of men and women at all levels, in all areas of work with equal access to recognition, reward and career progression opportunities.              I confirm the data reported is accurate.                            ANTON ROE  CHIEF EXECUTIVE  27 February 2018                                  2018 © copyright MHR  MHR, Ruddington Hall, Loughborough Road, Ruddington, Nottingham, NG11 6LL    TERMS OF USE  PRIVACY  CONTACT  HR and Payroll Solutions  HR Services           REQUEST A DEMO    Want a personalised demo? Please complete all fields and a member of the team will be in touch.          Please provide a valid value for First Name     Please provide a valid value for Last Name     Please provide a valid value for Email Address     Please provide a valid value for Contact Number     Please pr